SIMPLE: look
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Look
<hw>Look</hw> <pr>(l⟦oocr⟧k)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Looked</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Looking</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>loken</ets>,
AS. <ets>l⟦omac⟧cian</ets>; akin to G. <ets>lugen</ets>, OHG.
<ets>luog⟦emac⟧n</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To direct the eyes for
the purpose of seeing something; to direct the eyes toward an object; to
observe with the eyes while keeping them directed; -- with various
prepositions, often in a special or figurative sense. See Phrases
below.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To direct the attention (to something); to consider;
to examine; <as>as, to <ex>look</ex> at an action</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To seem; to appear; to have a particular appearance;
<as>as, the patient <ex>looks</ex> better; the clouds <ex>look</ex>
rainy.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It would <qex>look</qex> more like vanity than gratitude.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Observe how such a practice <qex>looks</qex> in another
person.</q> <rj><qau>I. Watts.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To have a particular direction or situation; to
face; to front.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The inner gate that <qex>looketh</qex> to north.</q>
<rj><qau>Ezek. viii. 3.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The east gate . . . which <qex>looketh</qex> eastward.</q>
<rj><qau>Ezek. xi. 1.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>In the imperative: see; behold; take notice; take
care; observe; -- used to call attention.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Look</qex>, how much we thus expel of sin, so much we expel
of virtue.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Look</xex>, in the imperative, may be followed by a
dependent sentence, but <xex>see</xex> is oftener so used.</note><-- See
spot run? in 1990, the reverse is true -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Look</qex> that ye bind them fast.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Look</qex> if it be my daughter.</q>
<rj><qau>Talfourd.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To show one's self in looking, as by leaning out of
a window; <as>as, <ex>look</ex> out of the window while I speak to
you</as>. Sometimes used figuratively.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>My toes <qex>look</qex> through the overleather.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>To await the appearance of anything; to expect; to
anticipate.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Looking</qex> each hour into death's mouth to fall.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<cs><p><col><b>To look about</b></col>, <cd>to look on all sides, or in
different directions.</cd> -- <col><b>To look about one</b></col>,
<cd>to be on the watch; to be vigilant; to be circumspect or
guarded.</cd> -- <col><b>To look after</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>To
attend to; to take care of; <as>as, <ex>to look after</ex>
children</as>.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>To expect; to be in a state of
expectation.</cd>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Men's hearts failing them for fear, and for <qex>looking
after</qex> those things which are coming on the earth.</q>
<rj><qau>Luke xxi. 26.</qau></rj></p>

<p><sd>(c)</sd> <cd>To seek; to search.</cd>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>My subject does not oblige me <qex>to look after</qex> the water,
or point forth the place where to it is now retreated.</q>
<rj><qau>Woodward.</qau></rj></p>

<p>-- <col><b>To look at</b></col>, <cd>to direct the eyes toward so
that one sees, or as if to see; <as>as, <ex>to look at</ex> a star</as>;
hence, to observe, examine, consider; <as>as, <ex>to look at</ex> a
matter without prejudice</as>.</cd> -- <col><b>To look black</b></col>,
<cd>to frown; to scowl; to have a threatening appearance.</cd>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The bishops thereat repined, and <qex>looked black</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Holinshed.</qau></rj></p>

<p>-- <mcol><col><b>To look down on</b></col> <it>or</it> <col><b>To
look down upon</b></col></mcol>, <cd>to treat with indifference or
contempt; to regard as an inferior; to despise.</cd> -- <col><b>To look
for</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>To expect; <as>as, <ex>to look for</ex>
news by the arrival of a ship</as>.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Look</xex> now
<xex>for</xex> no enchanting voice.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Milton.</au> <sd>(b)</sd>
<cd>To seek for; to search for; <as>as, <ex>to look for</ex> lost money,
or lost cattle</as>.</cd> -- <col><b>To look forth</b></col>.
<sd>(a)</sd> <cd>To look out of something, as from a window.</cd>
<sd>(b)</sd> <cd>To threaten to come out.</cd> <au>Jer. vi. 1. (Rev.
Ver.).</au> -- <col><b>To look forward to</b></col>. <cd>To anticipate
with an expectation of pleasure; to be eager for; <as>as, I am
<ex>looking forward to</ex> your visit</as>.</cd> -- <col><b>To look
into</b></col>, <cd>to inspect closely; to observe narrowly; to examine;
<as>as, <ex>to look into</ex> the works of nature; <ex>to look into</ex>
one's conduct or affairs</as>.</cd> -- <col><b>To look on</b></col>.
<sd>(a)</sd> <cd>To regard; to esteem.</cd>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Her friends would <qex>look on</qex> her the worse.</q>
<rj><qau>Prior.</qau></rj></p>

<p><sd>(b)</sd> <cd>To consider; to view; to conceive of; to think
of.</cd>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I <qex>looked on</qex> Virgil as a succinct, majestic writer.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj></p>

<p><sd>(c)</sd> <cd>To be a mere spectator.</cd>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I'll be a candleholder, and <qex>look on</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj></p>

<p>-- <col><b>To look out</b></col>, <cd>to be on the watch; to be
careful; as, the seaman <xex>looks out</xex> for breakers.</cd> --
<col><b>To look through</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>To see through.</cd>
<sd>(b)</sd> <cd>To search; to examine with the eyes.</cd> --
<mcol><col><b>To look to</b></col> <it>or</it> <col><b>To look
unto</b></col></mcol>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>To watch; to take care of.</cd>
⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Look</xex> well <xex>to</xex> thy herds.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Prov.
xxvii. 23.</au> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>To resort to with expectation of
receiving something; to expect to receive from; as, the creditor may
<xex>look to</xex> surety for payment.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Look unto</xex>
me, and be ye saved.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Is. xlv. 22.</au> -- <col><b>To look
up</b></col>, <cd>to search for or find out by looking; as, <xex>to look
up</xex> the items of an account.</cd> -- <col><b>To look up
to</b></col>, <cd>to respect; to regard with deference.</cd>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p></cs>

<p><ent>Look</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Look
<hw>Look</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To look at; to turn the
eyes toward.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To seek; to search for.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Looking</qex> my love, I go from place to place.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To expect.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To influence, overawe, or subdue by looks or
presence as, to <xex>look</xex> down opposition.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A spirit fit to start into an empire,⟦br⟧
And <qex>look</qex> the world to law.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To express or manifest by a look.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Soft eyes <qex>looked</qex> love to eyes which spake again.</q>
<rj><qau>Byron.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To look daggers</b></col>. <cd>See under
<er>Dagger</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>To look in the face</b></col>, <cd>to
face or meet with boldness or confidence; hence, sometimes, to meet for
combat.</cd> -- <col><b>To look out</b></col>, <cd>to seek for; to
search out; <as>as, prudent persons <ex>look out</ex> associates of good
reputation</as>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Look</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Look
<hw>Look</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of
looking; a glance; a sight; a view; -- often in certain phrases; <as>as,
to have, get, take, throw, or cast, a <ex>look</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Threw many a northward <qex>look</qex> to see his father⟦br⟧
Bring up his powers; but he did long in vain.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Expression of the eyes and face; manner; <as>as, a
proud or defiant <ex>look</ex></as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Gentle
<xex>looks</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Up ! up! my friends, and clear your <qex>looks</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Wordsworth.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <specif>Hence;</specif> <def>Appearance; aspect; <as>as,
the house has a gloomy <ex>look</ex>; the affair has a bad
<ex>look</ex>.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Pain, disgrace, and poverty have frighted <qex>looks</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There was something that reminded me of Dante's Hell in the
<qex>look</qex> of this.</q> <rj><qau>Carlyle.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>look-down</ent>⟦br⟧
<ent>lookdown</ent>⟦br⟧
<mhw>
